<paragraph blockId="4.[132,680,1784,1872]" lastBlockId="4.[718,1267,184,816]" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">
<emphasis box="[132,241,1785,1808]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">Discussion:</emphasis>
This species is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[636,680,1784,1808]" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">type</typeStatus>
locality in southwestern 
<collectingRegion box="[392,500,1816,1840]" country="Brazil" name="Amazonas" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[513,572,1816,1840]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[589,666,1816,1840]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="3.[95,174,1826,1845]" captionTargetBox="[98,1222,1034,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-94@3.[94,1228,1028,1803]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 11: Distribution records for four species of Paravelia; green square surrounded by a dotted line represents the type locality of P. cupariana, a new junior synonymy of P. spinifera." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4656560" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4656560/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). In the original description, the authors compared it with 
<emphasis box="[777,914,185,208]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">
<taxonomicName box="[777,910,185,208]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cupariana">P. cupariana</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
mentioning that although both species are loosely related to each other, 
<taxonomicName box="[1159,1266,217,240]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juruana">
<emphasis box="[1159,1266,217,240]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">P. juruana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the latter by its longer body (
<emphasis box="[1155,1266,249,272]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">
<taxonomicName box="[1155,1261,249,272]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juruana">P. juruana</taxonomicName>
:
</emphasis>
male 5.65, female 5.71; 
<emphasis box="[985,1119,281,304]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">
<taxonomicName box="[985,1114,281,304]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cupariana">P. cupariana</taxonomicName>
:
</emphasis>
male and female 3.57), and the first antennomere smaller than the width of head. Later, 
<bibRefCitation author="SPANGLER, P. J." box="[992,1161,344,368]" pageId="4" pageNumber="187" pagination="360 - 366" refId="ref3737" refString="SPANGLER, P. J. 1989. A new species of Neotropical water bug, Paravelia biae, from Brazil (Heteroptera: Veliidae). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 91 (3): 360 - 366." type="journal article" year="1989">Spangler (1989)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spangler" authorityYear="1989" box="[718,786,376,400]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biae">
<emphasis box="[718,786,376,400]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">P. biae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the State of Pará, northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1152,1214,376,400]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, and compared this species with 
<taxonomicName authority="(Berg, 1883)" baseAuthorityName="Berg" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[1013,1266,408,432]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="platensis">
<emphasis box="[1013,1122,408,432]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">P. platensis</emphasis>
(Berg, 1883)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hungerford, 1930)" baseAuthorityName="Hungerford" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[764,1098,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="williamsi">
<emphasis box="[764,880,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">P. williamsi</emphasis>
(Hungerford, 1930)
</taxonomicName>
, species that are not morphologically similar to one another. In fact, 
<taxonomicName box="[718,824,505,528]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juruana">
<emphasis box="[718,824,505,528]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">P. juruana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spangler" authorityYear="1989" box="[881,948,504,528]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biae">
<emphasis box="[881,948,504,528]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">P. biae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are more similar to each oth- er because both have the body color dark brown to blackish, posterior angle of the pronotum forming a digitiform process, and the basal macula of the fore wing does not start from the humeral angle and ends before the posterior margin of the pronotum. However, 
<taxonomicName box="[771,874,697,720]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="juruana">
<emphasis box="[771,874,697,720]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">P. juruana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the apical macula of the fore wing projected laterally in the posterior region (
<figureCitation box="[1185,1252,728,752]" captionStart="FIGURES 8‑10" captionStartId="3.[95,185,928,947]" captionTargetBox="[94,1228,338,905]" captionTargetId="figure-47@3.[94,1228,338,905]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 8‑10: Dorsal view of Paravelia spp.: (8) Paravelia juruana, male paratype, white arrow indicates digitiform process of posterior angle of pronotum; (9) P. cupariana syn. nov., female paratype, black arrow indicates the humeral angle; (10) P. spinifera (female from Ilha de Outeiro, Pará, Brazil)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4656558" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4656558/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
), whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spangler" authorityYear="1989" box="[837,904,760,784]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biae">
<emphasis box="[837,904,760,784]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">P. biae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is evenly ovate, without projections (
<bibRefCitation author="RODRIGUES, H. D. D. &amp; MOREIRA, F. F. F. &amp; NIESER, N. &amp; CHEN, P. P. &amp; MELO, A. L. &amp; DIAS-SILVA, K. &amp; GIEHL, N. F. S." box="[782,1027,792,816]" pageId="4" pageNumber="187" pagination="1 - 47" refId="ref3650" refString="RODRIGUES, H. D. D.; MOREIRA, F. F. F.; NIESER, N.; CHEN, P. P.; MELO, A. L.; DIAS-SILVA, K. &amp; GIEHL, N. F. S. 2014 b. The genus Paravelia Breddin, 1898 (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Veliidae) in Brazil, with descriptions of eight new species. Zootaxa, 3784 (1): 1 - 47." type="journal article" year="2014">
Rodrigues 
<emphasis box="[894,949,792,816]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="187">et al.,</emphasis>
2014b
</bibRefCitation>
: p. 22, fig. 13c).
</paragraph>
